"Van Den Besselaar E.J.M., Klein Tank A.M.G., Van Der Schrier G.","Influence of circulation types on temperature extremes in Europe",2010,"Theoretical and Applied Climatology","99","3-4",,"431","439",,,10.1007/s00704-009-0153-6,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-73149093385&partnerID=40&md5=c2f1882f2ccee3303df08654eebe8da7","Royal Netherlands Meteorological Institute (KNMI), PO Box 201, De Bilt 3730 AE, Netherlands","Van Den Besselaar, E.J.M., Royal Netherlands Meteorological Institute (KNMI), PO Box 201, De Bilt 3730 AE, Netherlands; Klein Tank, A.M.G., Royal Netherlands Meteorological Institute (KNMI), PO Box 201, De Bilt 3730 AE, Netherlands; Van Der Schrier, G., Royal Netherlands Meteorological Institute (KNMI), PO Box 201, De Bilt 3730 AE, Netherlands","The aim of this study is to determine the influence of atmospheric circulation on the recently observed changes in the number of warm days and cold days in Europe. The temperature series for stations in the European Climate Assessment and Data set project and the Grosswetterlagen (GWL) were used here. The temperature series were first adjusted for global warming before determining the indices for cold and warm extremes. The 29 GWLs were grouped in ten circulation types. Then, the number of days a certain circulation type occurred was determined for each winter (December, January and February) and summer (June, July and August). The relation between the circulation type frequencies and the temperature indices was modelled with a multi-regression fit over the period 1947-1974 and tested for the period 1974-2000. The difference between the observed indices and the calculated indices in the second period (using the fit coefficients for the first period) shows a warming effect for both winter and summer and for at least the warm day index, which is unaccounted for by the global warming trend. A simple snow model shows that variations in the European snow cover extent are likely influencing the cold and warm day indices in winter: there is a correlation between the decreasing trend of the snow cover extent in Europe and the increasing (decreasing) trend of the number of warm (cold) days for stations throughout Europe. © 2009 Springer-Verlag.",,"air temperature; atmospheric circulation; climate change; extreme event; global warming; modeling; snow cover; summer; winter; Europe",,,,,,"Armstrong, R., Brodzik, M., (2007) Northern Hemisphere EASE-grid Weekly Snow Cover and Sea Ice Extent Version 3. Digital Media., , National Snow and Ice Data Center Boulder; Bárdossy, A., Caspary, H., Detection of climate change in Europe by analyzing European atmospheric circulation patterns from 1881 to 1989 (1990) Theor Appl Climatol, 42, pp. 155-167. , 10.1007/BF00866871; Baur, F., Hess, P., Nagel, H., (1944) Kalendar der Grosswetterlagen Europas, pp. 1881-1939. , Bad Homburg Deutscher Wetterdienst; Braithwaite, R., Zhang, Y., Sensitivity of mass balance of five Swiss glaciers to temperature changes assessed by tuning a degree-day model (2000) J Glaciol, 46, pp. 7-14. , 10.3189/172756500781833511; Brohan, P., Kennedy, J., Harris, I., Tett, S., Jones, P., Uncertainty estimates in regional and global observed temperature changes: A new dataset from 1850 (2006) Geophys Res Lett, 111, p. 12; Brown, R., Northern Hemisphere snow cover variability and change, 1915-97 (2000) J Climate, 13, pp. 2339-2355. , 10.1175/1520-0442(2000)013<2339:NHSCVA>2.0.CO;2; Cahynová, M., Huth, R., Changes of atmospheric circulation in central Europe and their influence on climatic trends in the Czech Republic (2009) Theor Appl Climatol, 96, pp. 57-68. , 10.1007/s00704-008-0097-2; Chen, D., A monthly circulation climatology for Sweden and its application to a winter temperature case study (2000) International Journal of Climatology, 20 (10), pp. 1067-1076. , DOI 10.1002/1097-0088(200008)20:10<1067::AID-JOC528>3.0.CO;2-Q; Christensen, J., Hewitson, B., Busuioc, A., Chen, A., Gao, X., Held, I., Jones, R., Whet